with berg’s father providing a  loan the founders worked out of boxes at first developing a client base and working on paying back the loan and earning their own livings much to their surprise hb exceeded its business goals yearoveryear and attracted clients by tailoring financial plans and strategies to their specific needs today hb’s clients include some of atlanta’s wealthiest and most private families enlarge shoestring start david homrich left and andy berg turned a  loan into a wealth… more joann vitelli “the exception here is the high quality and the general rule is that this industry is pretty rogue and pretty loud” said w cliff oxford founder and ceo of entrepreneurial education company entrepreneur advisors inc homrich berg sponsors ea’s educational events “both andy and david were cpas that transitioned to wealth managers so you see that discipline of a cpa firm but you see the innovation of an entrepreneurial company” built on the ideal that clients’ needs come first homrich berg’s hb corporate culture and stable values have helped it continue to thrive over the past two decades — despite changes along the way that foundation has also helped them earn the trust of some of atlanta’s most important business leaders such as the home depot inc cofounder and atlanta falcons owner arthur blank blank became a client of the firm in  while serving as president and chief operating officer of home depot “they earned my trust” blank said “i like the quality of their services and the fact that they are always reliable — i can count on them in addition they provide thoughtful analysis they understand me and my goals” today hb has grown from managing less than  million assets in its early years to approximately  billion the company ranks first on atlanta business chronicle’s  list of the top  national association of personal financial advisors feeonly investment advisers and th on the top  list of financial planning and advisory firms with clients in  states the firm has stayed true to its founding mission of providing objective feeonly financial planning and investment management services without relying on the sale of financial products for commissions “there were plenty of firms out there that were offering financial planning and investment advice but it was all tied to the sale of financial products and therefore there was an inherent conflict of interest” homrich said “we felt that there would be an opportunity to build a successful company where we sat on the same side of the table as the client” because hb works with clients on a feeonly basis and doesn’t generate commissions through product sales its success “really depends on the increase of value of assets of clients and making sure they are well taken care of” said william “bill” rich an estate planning attorney and partner with holland and knight who has been referring clients to hb since the mid’s blank was so satisfied with hb’s service that when he left the home depot in  and established his family office he asked homrich to join him and preside over his finance and investment matters “as we were building amb group — our investment management and support services company and now the parent company of our operating businesses — i wanted the company’s foundation to be built with the ‘best’ david is that” blank said “beyond his expertise and talents our relationship while he was at homrich berg was built on trust and understanding” in the summer of  in one of the most difficult decisions homrich said he’s ever made he decided to leave the company he and berg founded just as it was beginning to flourish “we’d just gotten about  million under management we were building the business nicely and the future looked very bright” homrich said “in the end i was very much attracted to the idea of joining forces with arthur and seeing what i could help the blank family build” today five partners including berg own hb despite the exit of his business partner berg credits much of the company’s success to the foundation laid by homrich in the early years “i think the heavy lifting was done in those early years and we just kind of took it from there” berg said “it was a very friendly parting and homrich and i are still close friends and we still do work for not only arthur but for many members of arthur’s family” maintaining strong relationships whether it’s with clients or former partners is part of hb’s corporate culture with clients these relationships involve assisting them with financial planning and investment needs throughout their life hb works in tandem with clients’ accountants estate attorneys mortgage brokers or bankers to ensure a client’s financial goals are fulfilled howard s hirsch of counsel in the atlanta office of baker donelson bearman caldwell  berkowitz pc whose practice focuses on real estate investment trusts securities law and commercial transactions has referred people to homrich berg “all their clients feel that they are getting oneonone attention” hirsch said individual customized service is important to highnetworth clients interested in preserving and growing wealth said michael smith shareholder in baker donelson’s atlanta office who concentrates on tax and corporate law “for this firm and some other ones the source of the income is either from wealthy families that have multigenerations of wealth they are trying to preserve and invest and other sources are from people that have become successful in business” smith said “they get a large sum of money when they sell their business and they like to diversify” as a client since  businessman charlie yates sits on hb’s client advisory board while hb does a good job managing client requests yates said the strategic framework and support for clients is hb’s ultimate strength “they are very good on the investment side but they are even better at making sure they understand your situation and customizing your investment program based on your personal needs your personal risk profile and they give great service to help manage affairs” yates said despite its strength hb like many others felt the pain of the recession rather than altering its business strategy during tough times however hb stayed the course and focused on being even more communicative with clients during the downturn in the end berg said the recession helped strengthen the firm’s client relationships “we had conviction in our asset allocation and were committed not to change course in the end that strategy benefited our clients” berg said hb should be able to continue to grow through client referrals homrich said “i think they are in a very good spot and i think they will continue to do well as long as they continue to remain focused on taking care of the client and client’s needs ahead of their own” he said about homrich berg • founded  • address  peachtree road nw suite  atlanta  • total assets under management as of june   billion • total atlanta staff  • number of feepaying clients companywide   in atlanta source atlanta business chronicle book of lists bizspace spotlight sponsor listing property spotlight  ashwood see all bizspace properties industries banking  financial services suggested reading sponsor listing home of the day see all photos stunning home in old fourth ward see all homes of the day homrich  berg inc  products  services home about us membership networking inbox wall import address book photo albums find other professionals other resources frequently asked questions spam whitelist instructions copyright credit logos  images the complete marketeer manage subscriptions unsubscribe from emails careers  open positions contact us manage your subscriptions consumers find it find a market exclusive consumer leads find a job find candidates find a company search blogs search users search industry articles search discussionstopics find toolsproducts insurance news jobs find a job post a job find candidates articles for candidates articles for employers tal